* Also from attaching the analogue to the analogue is what he mentioned in his interpretation of Surah Al-Nahl regarding the correlation between verses containing various proofs of the perfection of His power Almighty and the wonder of His craftsmanship, where Glory be to Him used as evidence the wonders of the animal world and the oddities of the plant world, then followed it with the wonder of human creation. He Almighty said {And Allah has sent down rain from the sky and given life thereby to the earth after its lifelessness. Indeed in that is a sign for a people who listen. {65} And indeed, for you in grazing livestock is a lesson. We give you drink from what is in their bellies - between excretion and blood - pure milk, palatable to drinkers. {66} And from the fruits of the palm trees and grapevines you take intoxicant and good provision. Indeed in that is a sign for a people who reason. {67} And your Lord inspired to the bee, "Take for yourself among the mountains, houses, and among the trees and [in] that which they construct. {68} Then eat from all the fruits and follow the ways of your Lord laid down [for you]." There emerges from their bellies a drink, varying in colors, in which there is healing for people. Indeed in that is a sign for a people who give thought. {69} And Allah created you; then He will take you in death. And among you is he who is reversed to the most decrepit [old] age so that he will not know, after [having had] knowledge, a thing. Indeed, Allah is Knowing and Competent. {70}}
* Imam Al-Shawkani said: [When Glory be to Him used as evidence for His existence, perfection of His power, and wonder of His craftsmanship the wonders of the conditions of animals, He wanted to mention using as evidence for the objective the oddities of the conditions of plants, so He said {And Allah has sent down from the sky}].
* He said, may Allah have mercy on him: [When Glory be to Him mentioned some conditions of animals and what is in them of wonders of dazzling craftsmanship and characteristics of overwhelming power, He followed it with the wonders of human creation and what is in it of lessons, saying {And Allah created you; then He will take you in death}] (1)

* In his interpretation of Surah Al-Isra, he mentions the connection between the divine directives contained in this Surah, starting with His saying Almighty {Do not make [as equal] with Allah another deity and [thereby] become censured and forsaken. {22} And your Lord has decreed that you not worship except Him, and to parents, good treatment. Whether one or both of them reach old age [while] with you, say not to them [so much as], "uff," and do not repel them but speak to them a noble word. {23}} to His saying Almighty {That is from what your Lord has revealed to you, [O Muhammad], of wisdom. And do not make [as equal] with Allah another deity, lest you be thrown into Hell, blamed and banished. {39}}
Imam Al-Shawkani says: [When Glory be to Him summarized the deeds of righteousness in His saying 'And whoever desires the Hereafter and strives for it with the necessary effort while he is a believer' (1), He began detailing that, starting with the most noble of them, which is Monotheism, so He said 'Do not make [as equal] with Allah another deity', and the address is to the Prophet, peace be upon him and his family.] (2)

* In his interpretation of Surah Al-Naml, he clarifies the connection between the introduction of the Surah and the stories contained in it. He mentions that these stories are of the chapter of detailing after summarizing, where those stories came detailing His saying Almighty {And indeed, you are receiving the Qur'an from One, Wise and Knowing. {6}}. Regarding that, he says: [When Glory be to Him finished the story of Moses, He commenced the story of David and his son Solomon. These stories and what is before them and after them are like explanation and confirmation of His saying {And indeed, you are receiving the Qur'an from One, Wise and Knowing}.] (3).

